# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arthropod
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arthropod/aarhus-university-press] The University Press publishes approximately 70 new books per year and is particularly strong in archaeology, history, philosophy and literature as well as natural sciences.
[src:arthropod/aarhus-university-press] The press currently has more than 1,200 titles in stock of which 400 are in English and some few in German and French.
[src:arthropod/aarhus-university-press] The titles are sold and purposefully marketed abroad using distributors in the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:arthropod/aarhus-university-press] The press feels that the maintenance of a very high quality in graphic design, cover design, choice of paper and quality of printing, is crucial.
[src:arthropod/aarhus-university-press] Several press titles have been honored by the Association of Book Craftsmanship Forening for Boghaandværk and chosen to be part of their annual exhibition for the Best Book Craftsmanship Award, most recently in 2007 with the publications *Sima Qian.
[src:arthropod/aarhus-university-press] The press is currently a member of the Association of University Presses.
[src:arthropod/aaveqaspis] The name of the genus is a compound of the Greenlandic word *aaveq* ('walrus'), reflecting the likeness of the tail spines to the tusks of a walrus, and the Ancient Greek word ἀσπίς (*aspís*; 'shield').
[src:arthropod/aaveqaspis] Ineson to honour him for his studies of the Cambrian of North Greenland.
[src:arthropod/aaveqaspis] The taxonomic position of *A. inesoni* is unclear.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] An **abdomen** (also **belly** or **stomach** in vertebrates, or **metasoma** in arthropods) is the front part of the torso between the thorax (chest) and pelvis in humans and in other vertebrates.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The area occupied by the abdomen is called the abdominal cavity.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In arthropods, it is the posterior tagma of the body; it follows the thorax or cephalothorax.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In humans, the abdomen stretches from the thorax at the thoracic diaphragm to the pelvis at the pelvic brim.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The pelvic brim stretches from the lumbosacral joint (the intervertebral disc between L5 and S1) to the pubic symphysis and is the edge of the pelvic inlet.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The space above this inlet and under the thoracic diaphragm is termed the abdominal cavity.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The boundary of the abdominal cavity is the abdominal wall in the front and the peritoneal surface at the rear.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In vertebrates, the abdomen is a large body cavity enclosed by the abdominal muscles, at the front and to the sides, and by part of the vertebral column at the back.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Lower ribs can also enclose ventral and lateral walls.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdominal cavity is continuous with, and above, the pelvic cavity.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It is attached to the thoracic cavity by the diaphragm.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Structures such as the aorta, inferior vena cava and esophagus pass through the diaphragm.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Both the abdominal and pelvic cavities are lined by a serous membrane known as the parietal peritoneum.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] This membrane is continuous with the visceral peritoneum lining the organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdomen in vertebrates contains a number of organs belonging to, for instance, the digestive system, urinary system, and muscular system.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdominal cavity contains most organs of the digestive system, including the stomach, the small intestine, and the colon with its attached appendix.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Other digestive organs are known as the accessory digestive organs and include the liver, its attached gallbladder, and the pancreas, and these communicate with the rest of the system via various ducts.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The spleen, and organs of the urinary system including the kidneys, and adrenal glands also lie within the abdomen, along with many blood vessels including the aorta and inferior vena cava.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The urinary bladder, uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries may be seen as either abdominal organs or as pelvic organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Finally, the abdomen contains an extensive membrane called the peritoneum.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] A fold of peritoneum may completely cover certain organs, whereas it may cover only one side of organs that usually lie closer to the abdominal wall.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] This is called the retroperitoneum, and the kidneys and ureters are known as *retroperitoneal* organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] There are three layers of muscles in the abdominal wall.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] They are, from the outside to the inside: external oblique, internal oblique, and transverse abdominal.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The first three layers extend between the vertebral column, the lower ribs, the iliac crest and pubis of the hip.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] All of their fibers merge towards the midline and surround the rectus abdominis in a sheath before joining up on the opposite side at the linea alba.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Strength is gained by the criss-crossing of fibers, such that the external oblique runs downward and forward, the internal oblique upward and forward, and the transverse abdominal horizontally forward.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The transverse abdominal muscle is flat and triangular, with its fibers running horizontally.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It lies between the internal oblique and the underlying transverse fascia.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It originates from the inguinal ligament, costal cartilages 7–12, the iliac crest and thoracolumbar fascia.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Inserts into the conjoint tendon, xiphoid process, linea alba and the pubic crest.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The rectus abdominis muscles are long and flat.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The muscle is crossed by three fibrous bands called the tendinous intersections.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The rectus abdominis is enclosed in a thick sheath, formed as described above, by fibers from each of the three muscles of the lateral abdominal wall.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] They originate at the pubis bone, run up the abdomen on either side of the linea alba, and insert into the cartilages of the fifth, sixth, and seventh ribs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In the region of the groin, the inguinal canal, is a passage through the layers.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] This gap is where the testes can drop through the wall and where the fibrous cord from the uterus in the female runs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] This is also where weakness can form, and cause inguinal hernias.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The pyramidalis muscle is small and triangular.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It is located in the lower abdomen in front of the rectus abdominis.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It originates at the pubic bone and is inserted into the linea alba halfway up to the navel.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Functionally, the human abdomen is where most of the digestive tract is placed and so most of the absorption and digestion of food occurs here.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The alimentary tract in the abdomen consists of the lower esophagus, the stomach, the duodenum, the jejunum, ileum, the cecum and the appendix, the ascending, transverse and descending colons, the sigmoid colon and the rectum.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Other vital organs inside the abdomen include the liver, the kidneys, the pancreas and the spleen.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdominal wall is split into the posterior (back), lateral (sides), and anterior (front) walls.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdominal muscles have different important functions.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] They assist as muscles of exhalation in the breathing process during forceful exhalation.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Moreover, these muscles serve as protection for the inner organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Furthermore, together with the back muscles they provide postural support and are important in defining the form.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] When the glottis is closed and the thorax and pelvis are fixed, they are integral in the cough, urination, defecation, childbirth, vomit, and singing functions.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] When the pelvis is fixed, they can initiate the movement of the trunk in a forward motion.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] When the thorax is fixed, they can pull up the pelvis and finally, they can bend the vertebral column sideways and assist in the trunk's rotation.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The transverse abdominis muscle is the deepest muscle; therefore, it cannot be touched from the outside.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It can greatly affect the body's posture.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The internal obliques are also deep and also affect body posture.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Both of them are involved in rotation and lateral flexion of the spine and are used to bend and support the spine from the front.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The external obliques are more superficial and are also involved in rotation and lateral flexion of the spine.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] They also stabilize the spine when upright.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The rectus abdominis muscle is not the most superficial abdominal muscle.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The tendonous sheath extending from the external obliques cover the rectus abdominis.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The rectus abdominis is the muscle that very fit people develop into "six-pack" abs, though there are five vertical sections on each side.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The two bottom sections are just above the pubic bone and usually not visible.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The rectus abdominals' function is to bend one's back forward (flexion).
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The main work of the abdominal muscles is to bend the spine forward when contracting concentrically.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Social and cultural perceptions of the outward appearance of the abdomen has varying significance around the world.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Depending on the type of society, excess weight can be perceived as an indicator of wealth and prestige due to excess food, or as a sign of poor health due to lack of exercise.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In many cultures, bare abdomens are distinctly sexualized and perceived similarly to breast cleavage.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Being key elements of spinal support, and contributors to good posture, it is important to properly exercise the abdominal muscles together with the back muscles because when these are weak or overly tight they can suffer painful spasms and injuries.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] When properly exercised, abdominal muscles contribute to improved posture and balance, reduce the likelihood of back pain episodes, reduce the severity of back pain, protect against injury, help avoid some back surgeries, and help with the healing of back problems, or after spine surgery.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] When strengthened, the abdominal muscles provide flexibility as well.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdominal muscles can be worked by strength and fitness exercises, and through practicing disciplines of general body strength such as Pilates, yoga, tai chi, and jogging.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Abdominal obesity is a condition where abdominal fat or visceral fat, has built up excessively between the abdominal organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] This is associated with a higher risk of heart disease, asthma and type 2 diabetes.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Abdominal trauma is an injury to the abdomen and can involve damage to the abdominal organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] There is an associated risk of severe blood loss and infection.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Injury to the lower chest can cause injuries to the spleen and liver.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] A scaphoid abdomen is when the abdomen is sucked inwards.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In a newborn, it may represent a diaphragmatic hernia.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In general, it is indicative of malnutrition.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Many gastrointestinal diseases affect the abdominal organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] These include stomach disease, liver disease, pancreatic disease, gallbladder and bile duct disease; intestinal diseases include enteritis, coeliac disease, diverticulitis, and irritable bowel syndrome.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Different medical procedures can be used to examine the organs of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] These include endoscopy, colonoscopy, sigmoidoscopy, enteroscopy, oesophagogastroduodenoscopy and virtual colonoscopy.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] There are also a number of medical imaging techniques that can be used.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Surface landmarks are important in the examination of the abdomen.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In the mid-line, a slight furrow extends from the xiphoid process above to the pubic symphysis below, representing the linea alba in the abdominal wall.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] At about its midpoint sits the umbilicus or navel.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The rectus abdominis on each side of the linea alba stands out in muscular people.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The outline of these muscles is interrupted by three or more transverse depressions indicating the tendinous intersections.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] There is usually one about the xiphoid process, one at the navel, and one in between.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It is the combination of the linea alba and the tendinous intersections which form the abdominal "six-pack" sought after by many people.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The upper lateral limit of the abdomen is the subcostal margin (at or near the *subcostal plane*) formed by the cartilages of the false ribs (8, 9, 10) joining one another.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The lower lateral limit is the anterior crest of the ilium and Poupart's ligament, which runs from the anterior superior spine of the ilium to the spine of the pubis.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] These lower limits are marked by visible grooves.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Just above the pubic spines on either side are the external abdominal rings, which are openings in the muscular wall of the abdomen through which the spermatic cord emerges in the male, and through which an inguinal hernia may rupture.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] One method by which the location of the abdominal contents can be appreciated is to draw three horizontal and two vertical lines.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The two vertical or mid-Poupart lines are drawn from the point midway between the anterior superior spine and the pubic symphysis on each side, vertically upward to the costal margin.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The right subcostal margin corresponds to the lower limit of the liver, while the right nipple is about half an inch above its upper limit.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdomen can be divided into quadrants or regions to describe the location of an organ or structure.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Classically, quadrants are described as the left upper, left lower, right upper, and right lower.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Quadrants are also often used in describing the site of an abdominal pain.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdomen can also be divided into nine regions.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] These terms stem from "hypo" meaning "below" and "epi" means "above", while "chondron" means "cartilage" (in this case, the cartilage of the rib) and "gaster" means stomach.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The "right iliac fossa" (RIF) is a common site of pain and tenderness in patients who have appendicitis.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The fossa is named for the underlying iliac fossa of the hip bone, and thus is somewhat imprecise.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Most of the anatomical structures that will produce pain and tenderness in this region are not in fact in the concavity of the ileum.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Abdominal organs can be highly specialized in some mammals.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] For example, the stomach of ruminants, (a suborder of mammals that includes cattle and sheep), is divided into four chambers – rumen, reticulum, omasum and abomasum.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In arthropods, the abdomen is built up of a series of upper plates known as tergites and lower plates known as sternites, the whole being held together by a tough yet stretchable membrane.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In insects, the abdomen contains the insect's digestive tract and reproductive organs.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] It consists of eleven segments in most orders of insects, though the eleventh segment is absent in the adult of most higher orders.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The number of these segments does vary from species to species with the number of segments visible reduced to only seven in the common honey bee.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In the Collembola (springtails), the abdomen has only six segments.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The abdomen is sometimes highly modified.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In Apocrita (bees, ants and wasps), the first segment of the abdomen is fused to the thorax and is called the propodeum.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In ants, the second segment forms the narrow petiole.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Some ants have an additional postpetiole segment, and the remaining segments form the bulbous gaster.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] The petiole and gaster (abdominal segments 2 and onward) are collectively called the metasoma.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Unlike other arthropods, insects possess no legs on the abdomen in adult form, though the Protura do have rudimentary leg-like appendages on the first three abdominal segments, and Archaeognatha possess small, articulated "styli" which are sometimes considered to be rudimentary appendages.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] Many larval insects including the Lepidoptera and the Symphyta (sawflies) have fleshy appendages called prolegs on their abdominal segments (as well as their more familiar thoracic legs), which allow them to grip onto the edges of plant leaves as they walk around.
[src:arthropod/abdomen] In arachnids (spiders, scorpions and relatives), the term "abdomen" is used interchangeably with "opisthosoma" ("hind body"), which is the body section posterior to that bearing the legs and head (the prosoma or cephalothorax).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:arthropod/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:arthropod/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:arthropod/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:arthropod/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Haemolymph is the analogue of blood for most arthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] An arthropod has an open circulatory system, with a body cavity called a haemocoel through which haemolymph circulates to the interior organs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Like their exteriors, the internal organs of arthropods are generally built of repeated segments.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] They have ladder-like nervous systems, with paired ventral nerve cords running through all segments and forming paired ganglia in each segment.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Their heads are formed by fusion of varying numbers of segments, and their brains are formed by fusion of the ganglia of these segments and encircle the esophagus.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The respiratory and excretory systems of arthropods vary, depending as much on their environment as on the subphylum to which they belong.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods use combinations of compound eyes and pigment-pit ocelli for vision.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In most species, the ocelli can only detect the direction from which light is coming, and the compound eyes are the main source of information; however, in spiders, the main eyes are ocelli that can form images and, in a few cases, can swivel to track prey.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods also have a wide range of chemical and mechanical sensors, mostly based on modifications of the many bristles known as setae that project through their cuticles.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Similarly, their reproduction and development are varied; all terrestrial species use internal fertilization, but this is sometimes by indirect transfer of the sperm via an appendage or the ground, rather than by direct injection.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Aquatic species use either internal or external fertilization.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Almost all arthropods lay eggs, with many species giving birth to live young after the eggs have hatched inside the mother.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Still, a few are genuinely viviparous, such as aphids.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropod hatchlings vary from miniature adults to grubs and caterpillars that lack jointed limbs and eventually undergo a total metamorphosis to produce the adult form.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The level of maternal care for hatchlings varies from nonexistent to the prolonged care provided by social insects.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The evolutionary ancestry of arthropods dates back to the Cambrian period.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The group is generally regarded as monophyletic, and many analyses support the placement of arthropods with cycloneuralians (or their constituent clades) in a superphylum Ecdysozoa.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Overall, however, the basal relationships of animals are not yet well resolved.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Likewise, the relationships between various arthropod groups are still actively debated.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Today, arthropods contribute to the human food supply both directly as food and more importantly, indirectly as pollinators of crops.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Some species are known to spread severe disease to humans, livestock, and crops.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The word *arthropod* comes from the Greek ἄρθρον *árthron* 'joint', and πούς *poús* (gen. ποδός *podós*) 'foot' or 'leg', which together mean "jointed leg", with the word "arthropodes" initially used in anatomical descriptions by Barthélemy Charles Joseph Dumortier published in 1832.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The designation "Arthropoda" appears to have been first used in 1843 by the German zoologist Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst (1777–1857).
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The origin of the name has been the subject of considerable confusion, with credit often given erroneously to Pierre André Latreille or Karl Theodor Ernst von Siebold instead, among various others.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Terrestrial arthropods are often called bugs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods are invertebrates with segmented bodies and jointed limbs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The exoskeleton or cuticle consists of chitin, a polymer of *N*-acetylglucosamine.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The cuticle of many crustaceans, beetle mites, the clades Penetini and Archaeoglenini inside the beetle subfamily Phrenapatinae, and millipedes (except for bristly millipedes) is also biomineralized with calcium carbonate.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Calcification of the endosternite, an internal structure used for muscle attachments, also occurs in some opiliones, and the pupal cuticle of the fly *Bactrocera dorsalis* contains calcium phosphate.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropoda is the largest animal phylum, with the estimates of the number of arthropod species varying from 1,170,000 to 5~10 million and accounting for over 80 percent of all known living animal species.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] One arthropod sub-group, the insects, includes more described species than any other taxonomic class.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The total number of species remains difficult to determine, as estimates rely on census counts at specific locations, scaled up and projected onto other regions, then totalled – allowing for double-counting – to cover the whole world.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Modeling assumptions are involved at each stage, introducing uncertainty.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A study in 1992 estimated that there were 500,000 species of animals and plants in Costa Rica alone, of which 365,000 were arthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] They are important members of marine, freshwater, land and air ecosystems and one of only two major animal groups that have adapted to life in dry environments; the other is amniotes, whose living members are reptiles, birds and mammals.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Both the smallest and largest arthropods are crustaceans.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The smallest belong to the class Tantulocarida, some of which are less than 100 micrometres (0.0039 in) long.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The largest are species in the class Malacostraca, with the legs of the Japanese spider crab potentially spanning up to 4 metres (13 ft) and the American lobster reaching weights over 20 kg (44 lbs).
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The embryos of all arthropods are segmented, consisting of a series of repeated modules.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The last common ancestor of living arthropods probably consisted of a series of undifferentiated segments, each with a pair of appendages that functioned as limbs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, all known living and fossil arthropods have grouped segments into tagmata in which segments and their limbs are specialized in various ways.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The three-part appearance of many insect bodies and the two-part appearance of spiders is a result of this grouping.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] There are no external signs of segmentation in mites.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods also have two body elements that are not part of this serially repeated pattern of segments, an ocular somite at the front, where the mouth and eyes originated, and a telson at the rear, behind the anus.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Originally, it seems that each appendage-bearing segment had two separate pairs of appendages: an upper, unsegmented exite and a lower, segmented endopod.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] These would later fuse into a single pair of biramous appendages united by a basal segment (protopod or basipod), with the upper branch acting as a gill while the lower branch was used for locomotion.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The appendages of most crustaceans and some extinct taxa such as trilobites have another segmented branch known as exopods, but whether these structures have a single origin remain controversial.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Alignment of anterior body segments and appendages across various arthropod taxa, based on the observations until the mid 2010s.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The most conspicuous specialization of segments is in the head.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Despite myriapods and hexapods both having similar head combinations, hexapods are deeply nested within crustacea while myriapods are not, so these traits are believed to have evolved separately.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In addition, some extinct arthropods, such as *Marrella*, belong to none of these groups, as their heads are formed by their own particular combinations of segments and specialized appendages.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Working out the evolutionary stages by which all these different combinations could have appeared is so difficult that it has long been known as "The arthropod head problem".
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Snodgrass even hoped it would not be solved, as he found trying to work out solutions to be fun.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropod exoskeletons are made of cuticle, a non-cellular material secreted by the epidermis.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The exocuticle and endocuticle together are known as the procuticle.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Each body segment and limb section is encased in hardened cuticle.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The joints between body segments and between limb sections are covered by flexible cuticle.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The exoskeletons of most aquatic crustaceans are biomineralized with calcium carbonate extracted from the water.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Some terrestrial crustaceans have developed means of storing the mineral, since on land they cannot rely on a steady supply of dissolved calcium carbonate.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Biomineralization generally affects the exocuticle and the outer part of the endocuticle.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The cuticle may have setae (bristles) growing from special cells in the epidermis.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Setae are as varied in form and function as appendages.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The exoskeleton cannot stretch and thus restricts growth.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods, therefore, replace their exoskeletons by undergoing ecdysis (moulting), or shedding the old exoskeleton, the exuviae, after growing a new one that is not yet hardened.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Moulting cycles run nearly continuously until an arthropod reaches full size.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The developmental stages between each moult (ecdysis) until sexual maturity is reached is called an instar.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Differences between instars can often be seen in altered body proportions, colors, patterns, changes in the number of body segments or head width.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] After moulting, i.e. shedding their exoskeleton, the juvenile arthropods continue in their life cycle until they either pupate or moult again.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In the initial phase of moulting, the animal stops feeding and its epidermis releases moulting fluid, a mixture of enzymes that digests the endocuticle and thus detaches the old cuticle.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] This phase begins when the epidermis has secreted a new epicuticle to protect it from the enzymes, and the epidermis secretes the new exocuticle while the old cuticle is detaching.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] When this stage is complete, the animal's body swells by taking in a large quantity of water or air, causing the old cuticle to split along predefined weaknesses where the old exocuticle was thinnest.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] It commonly takes several minutes for the animal to struggle out of the old cuticle.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] At this point, the new one is wrinkled and so soft that the animal cannot support itself and finds it very difficult to move, and the new endocuticle has not yet formed.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The animal continues to pump itself up to stretch the new cuticle as much as possible, then hardens the new exocuticle and eliminates the excess air or water.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] By the end of this phase, the new endocuticle has formed.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Many arthropods then eat the discarded cuticle to reclaim its materials.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Because arthropods are unprotected and nearly immobilized until the new cuticle has hardened, they are in danger both of being trapped in the old cuticle and of being attacked by predators.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Moulting may be responsible for 80 to 90% of all arthropod deaths.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropod bodies are also segmented internally, and the nervous, muscular, circulatory, and excretory systems have repeated components.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods come from a lineage of animals that have a coelom, a membrane-lined cavity between the gut and the body wall that accommodates the internal organs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The strong, segmented limbs of arthropods eliminate the need for one of the coelom's main ancestral functions, as a hydrostatic skeleton, which muscles compress in order to change the animal's shape and thus enable it to move.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Hence the coelom of the arthropod is reduced to small areas around the reproductive and excretory systems.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Its place is largely taken by a hemocoel, a cavity that runs most of the length of the body and through which blood flows.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods have open circulatory systems.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Most have a few short, open-ended arteries.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In chelicerates and crustaceans, the blood carries oxygen to the tissues, while hexapods use a separate system of tracheae.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Many crustaceans and a few chelicerates and tracheates use respiratory pigments to assist oxygen transport.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The most common respiratory pigment in arthropods is copper-based hemocyanin; this is used by many crustaceans and a few centipedes.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A few crustaceans and insects use iron-based haemoglobin, the respiratory pigment used by vertebrates.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] As with other invertebrates, the respiratory pigments of those arthropods that have them are generally dissolved in the blood and rarely enclosed in corpuscles as they are in vertebrates.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The heart is a muscular tube that runs just under the back and for most of the length of the hemocoel.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] It contracts in ripples that run from rear to front, pushing blood forwards.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Sections not being squeezed by the heart muscle are expanded either by elastic ligaments or by small muscles, in either case connecting the heart to the body wall.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Along the heart run a series of paired ostia, non-return valves that allow blood to enter the heart but prevent it from leaving before it reaches the front.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods have a wide variety of respiratory systems.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Small species often do not have any, since their high ratio of surface area to volume enables simple diffusion through the body surface to supply enough oxygen.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Crustacea usually have gills that are modified appendages.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Tracheae, systems of branching tunnels that run from the openings in the body walls, deliver oxygen directly to individual cells in many insects, myriapods and arachnids.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Living arthropods have paired main nerve cords running along their bodies below the gut, and in each segment the cords form a pair of ganglia from which sensory and motor nerves run to other parts of the segment.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Although the pairs of ganglia in each segment often appear physically fused, they are connected by commissures (relatively large bundles of nerves), which give arthropod nervous systems a characteristic ladder-like appearance.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The brain is in the head, encircling and mainly above the oesophagus.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] It consists of the fused ganglia of the acron and one or two of the foremost segments that form the head – a total of three pairs of ganglia in most arthropods, but only two in chelicerates, which do not have antennae or the ganglion connected to them.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The ganglia of other head segments are often close to the brain and function as part of it.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In insects, these other head ganglia combine into a pair of subesophageal ganglia, under and behind the oesophagus.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Spiders take this process a step further, as all the segmental ganglia are incorporated into the subesophageal ganglia, which occupy most of the space in the cephalothorax (front "super-segment").
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] There are two different types of arthropod excretory systems.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In aquatic arthropods, the end-product of biochemical reactions that metabolise nitrogen is ammonia, which is so toxic that it needs to be diluted as much as possible with water.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The ammonia is then eliminated via any permeable membrane, mainly through the gills.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] All crustaceans use this system, and its high consumption of water may be responsible for the relative lack of success of crustaceans as land animals.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Most aquatic arthropods and some terrestrial ones also have organs called nephridia ("little kidneys"), which extract other wastes for excretion as urine.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The stiff cuticles of arthropods would block out information about the outside world, except that they are penetrated by many sensors or connections from sensors to the nervous system.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In fact, arthropods have modified their cuticles into elaborate arrays of sensors.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Various touch sensors, mostly setae, respond to different levels of force, from strong contact to very weak air currents.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Chemical sensors provide equivalents of taste and smell, often by means of setae.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Pressure sensors often take the form of membranes that function as eardrums, but are connected directly to nerves rather than to auditory ossicles.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The antennae of most hexapods include sensor packages that monitor humidity, moisture and temperature.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Most arthropods lack balance and acceleration sensors, and rely on their eyes to tell them which way is up.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The self-righting behaviour of cockroaches is triggered when pressure sensors on the underside of the feet report no pressure.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, many malacostracan crustaceans have statocysts, which provide the same sort of information as the balance and motion sensors of the vertebrate inner ear.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The proprioceptors of arthropods, sensors that report the force exerted by muscles and the degree of bending in the body and joints, are well understood.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, little is known about what other internal sensors arthropods may have.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods may have sophisticated visual systems that include one or more usually both of compound eyes and pigment-cup ocelli, ("little eyes").
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In most cases, ocelli are only capable of detecting the direction from which light is coming, using the shadow cast by the walls of the cup, although the main eyes of spiders are pigment-cup ocelli that are capable of forming images, and those of jumping spiders can rotate to track prey.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Compound eyes consist of fifteen to several thousand independent ommatidia, columns that are usually hexagonal in cross section.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Each ommatidium is an independent sensor, with its own light-sensitive cells and often with its own lens and cornea.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Compound eyes have a wide field of view, and can detect fast movement and, in some cases, the polarization of light.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] On the other hand, the relatively large size of ommatidia makes the images rather coarse, and compound eyes are shorter-sighted than those of birds and mammals – although this is not a severe disadvantage, as objects and events within 20 cm (8 in) are most important to most arthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Several arthropods have colour vision, and that of some insects has been studied in detail; for example, the ommatidia of bees contain receptors for both green and ultra-violet.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A few arthropods, such as barnacles, are hermaphroditic, that is, each can have the organs of both sexes.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, individuals of most species remain of one sex their entire lives.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A few species of insects and crustaceans can reproduce by parthenogenesis, especially if conditions favour a "population explosion".
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, most arthropods rely on sexual reproduction, and parthenogenetic species often revert to sexual reproduction when conditions become less favourable.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The ability to undergo meiosis is widespread among arthropods including both those that reproduce sexually and those that reproduce parthenogenetically.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Although meiosis is a major characteristic of arthropods, understanding of its fundamental adaptive benefit has long been regarded as an unresolved problem, that appears to have remained unsettled.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Aquatic arthropods may breed by external fertilization, as for example horseshoe crabs do, or by internal fertilization, where the ova remain in the female's body and the sperm must somehow be inserted.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] All known terrestrial arthropods use internal fertilization.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Opiliones (harvestmen), millipedes, and some crustaceans use modified appendages such as gonopods or penises to transfer the sperm directly to the female.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, most male terrestrial arthropods produce spermatophores, waterproof packets of sperm, which the females take into their bodies.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A few such species rely on females to find spermatophores that have already been deposited on the ground, but in most cases males only deposit spermatophores when complex courtship rituals look likely to be successful.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Most arthropods lay eggs, but scorpions are ovoviviparous: they produce live young after the eggs have hatched inside the mother, and are noted for prolonged maternal care.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Newly born arthropods have diverse forms, and insects alone cover the range of extremes.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Some hatch as apparently miniature adults (direct development), and in some cases, such as silverfish, the hatchlings do not feed and may be helpless until after their first moult.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Many insects (Holometabola) hatch as grubs or caterpillars, which do not have segmented limbs or hardened cuticles, and metamorphose into adult forms by entering an inactive phase in which the larval tissues are broken down and re-used to build the adult body.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Dragonfly larvae have the typical cuticles and jointed limbs of arthropods but are flightless water-breathers with extendable jaws.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Crustaceans commonly hatch as tiny nauplius larvae that have only three segments and pairs of appendages.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Based on the distribution of shared plesiomorphic features in extant and fossil taxa, the last common ancestor of all arthropods is inferred to have been as a modular organism with each module covered by its own sclerite (armour plate) and bearing a pair of biramous limbs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, whether the ancestral limb was uniramous or biramous is far from a settled debate.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] This Ur-arthropod had a ventral mouth, pre-oral antennae and dorsal eyes at the front of the body.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] It has been proposed that the Ediacaran animals *Parvancorina* and *Spriggina*, from around 555 million years ago, were arthropods, but later study shows that their affinities of being origin of arthropods are not reliable.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Small arthropods with bivalve-like shells have been found in Early Cambrian fossil beds dating 541 to 539 million years ago in China and Australia.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The earliest Cambrian trilobite fossils are about 520 million years old, but the class was already quite diverse and worldwide, suggesting that they had been around for quite some time.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In the Maotianshan shales, which date back to 518 million years ago, arthropods such as *Kylinxia* and *Erratus* have been found that seem to represent transitional fossils between stem (e.g.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Radiodonta such as *Anomalocaris*) and true arthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Re-examination in the 1970s of the Burgess Shale fossils from about 505 million years ago identified many arthropods, some of which could not be assigned to any of the well-known groups, and thus intensified the debate about the Cambrian explosion.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A fossil of *Marrella* from the Burgess Shale has provided the earliest clear evidence of moulting.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The earliest fossil of likely pancrustacean larvae date from about 514 million years ago in the Cambrian, followed by unique taxa like *Yicaris* and *Wujicaris*.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The purported pancrustacean/crustacean affinity of some cambrian arthropods (e.g.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Phosphatocopina, Bradoriida and Hymenocarine taxa like waptiids) were disputed by subsequent studies, as they might branch before the mandibulate crown-group.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Within the pancrustacean crown-group, only Malacostraca, Branchiopoda and Pentastomida have Cambrian fossil records.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Crustacean fossils are common from the Ordovician period onwards.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] They have remained almost entirely aquatic, possibly because they never developed excretory systems that conserve water.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods provide the earliest identifiable fossils of land animals, from about 419 million years ago in the Late Silurian, and terrestrial tracks from about 450 million years ago appear to have been made by arthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Arthropods possessed attributes that were easily coopted for life on land; their existing jointed exoskeletons provided protection against desiccation, support against gravity and a means of locomotion that was not dependent on water.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Around the same time the aquatic, scorpion-like eurypterids became the largest ever arthropods, some as long as 2.5 m (8 ft 2 in).
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The oldest known arachnid is the trigonotarbid *Palaeotarbus jerami*, from about 420 million years ago in the Silurian period.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] *Attercopus fimbriunguis*, from 386 million years ago in the Devonian period, bears the earliest known silk-producing spigots, but its lack of spinnerets means it was not one of the true spiders, which first appear in the Late Carboniferous over 299 million years ago.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The Jurassic and Cretaceous periods provide a large number of fossil spiders, including representatives of many modern families.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The oldest known scorpion is *Dolichophonus,* dated back to 436 million years ago.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Lots of Silurian and Devonian scorpions were previously thought to be gill-breathing, hence the idea that scorpions were primitively aquatic and evolved air-breathing book lungs later on.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However subsequent studies reveal most of them lacking reliable evidence for an aquatic lifestyle, while exceptional aquatic taxa (e.g.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] *Waeringoscorpio*) most likely derived from terrestrial scorpion ancestors.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The oldest fossil record of hexapod is obscure, as most of the candidates are poorly preserved and their hexapod affinities had been disputed.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] An iconic example is the Devonian *Rhyniognatha hirsti*, dated at 396 to 407 million years ago, its mandibles are thought to be a type found only in winged insects, which suggests that the earliest insects appeared in the Silurian period.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, later study shows that *Rhyniognatha* most likely represent a myriapod, not even a hexapod.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The unequivocal oldest known hexapod is the springtail *Rhyniella*, from about 410 million years ago in the Devonian period, and the palaeodictyopteran *Delitzschala bitterfeldensis*, from about 325 million years ago in the Carboniferous period, respectively.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The Mazon Creek lagerstätten from the Late Carboniferous, about 300 million years ago, include about 200 species, some gigantic by modern standards, and indicate that insects had occupied their main modern ecological niches as herbivores, detritivores and insectivores.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Social termites and ants first appear in the Early Cretaceous, and advanced social bees have been found in Late Cretaceous rocks but did not become abundant until the Middle Cenozoic.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] From 1952 to 1977, zoologist Sidnie Manton and others argued that arthropods are polyphyletic, in other words, that they do not share a common ancestor that was itself an arthropod.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Instead, they proposed that three separate groups of "arthropods" evolved separately from common worm-like ancestors: the chelicerates, including spiders and scorpions; the crustaceans; and the uniramia, consisting of onychophorans, myriapods and hexapods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] These arguments usually bypassed trilobites, as the evolutionary relationships of this class were unclear.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Further analysis and discoveries in the 1990s reversed this view, and led to acceptance that arthropods are monophyletic, in other words they are inferred to share a common ancestor that was itself an arthropod.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] These changes made the scope of the term "arthropod" unclear, and Claus Nielsen proposed that the wider group should be labelled "Panarthropoda" ("all the arthropods") while the animals with jointed limbs and hardened cuticles should be called "Euarthropoda" ("true arthropods").
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] A contrary view was presented in 2003, when Jan Bergström and Hou Xian-guang argued that, if arthropods were a "sister-group" to any of the anomalocarids, they must have lost and then re-evolved features that were well-developed in the anomalocarids.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The earliest known arthropods ate mud in order to extract food particles from it, and possessed variable numbers of segments with unspecialized appendages that functioned as both gills and legs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Anomalocarids were, by the standards of the time, huge and sophisticated predators with specialized mouths and grasping appendages, fixed numbers of segments some of which were specialized, tail fins, and gills that were very different from those of arthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In 2006, they suggested that arthropods were more closely related to lobopods and tardigrades than to anomalocarids.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In 2014, it was found that tardigrades were more closely related to arthropods than velvet worms.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Higher up the "family tree", the Annelida have traditionally been considered the closest relatives of the Panarthropoda, since both groups have segmented bodies, and the combination of these groups was labelled Articulata.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] There had been competing proposals that arthropods were closely related to other groups such as nematodes, priapulids and tardigrades, but these remained minority views because it was difficult to specify in detail the relationships between these groups.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In the 1990s, molecular phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences produced a coherent scheme showing arthropods as members of a superphylum labelled Ecdysozoa ("animals that moult"), which contained nematodes, priapulids and tardigrades but excluded annelids.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] This hypothesis groups annelids with molluscs and brachiopods in another superphylum, Lophotrochozoa.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] If the Ecdysozoa hypothesis is correct, then segmentation of arthropods and annelids either has evolved convergently or has been inherited from a much older ancestor and subsequently lost in several other lineages, such as the non-arthropod members of the Ecdysozoa.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] *Marrella* was the first one to be recognized as significantly different from the well-known groups.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The Deuteropoda is a recently established clade uniting the crown-group (living) arthropods with these possible "upper stem-group" fossils taxa.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The clade is defined by important changes to the structure of the head region such as the appearance of a differentiated deutocerebral appendage pair, which excludes more basal taxa like radiodonts and "gilled lobopodians".
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Controversies remain about the positions of various extinct arthropod groups.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Some studies recover Megacheira as closely related to chelicerates, while others recover them as outside the group containing Chelicerate and Mandibulata as stem-group euarthropods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The placement of the Artiopoda (which contains the extinct trilobites and similar forms) is also a frequent subject of dispute.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The main hypotheses position them in the clade Arachnomorpha with the Chelicerates.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] However, one of the newer hypotheses is that the chelicerae have originated from the same pair of appendages that evolved into antennae in the ancestors of Mandibulata, which would place trilobites, which had antennae, closer to Mandibulata than Chelicerata, in the clade Antennulata.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The fuxianhuiids, usually suggested to be stem-group arthropods, have been suggested to be Mandibulates in some recent studies.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The Hymenocarina, a group of bivalved arthropods, previously thought to have been stem-group members of the group, have been demonstrated to be mandibulates based on the presence of mandibles.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] **Chelicerates** comprise the marine sea spiders and horseshoe crabs, along with the terrestrial arachnids such as mites, harvestmen, spiders, scorpions and related organisms characterized by the presence of chelicerae, appendages just above/in front of the mouthparts.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Chelicerae appear in scorpions and horseshoe crabs as tiny claws that they use in feeding, but those of spiders have developed as fangs that inject venom.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] **Myriapods** comprise millipedes, centipedes, pauropods and symphylans, characterized by having numerous body segments each of which bearing one or two pairs of legs (or in a few cases being legless).
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] All members are exclusively terrestrial.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] **Pancrustaceans** comprise ostracods, barnacles, copepods, malacostracans, cephalocaridans, branchiopods, remipedes and hexapods.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Most groups are primarily aquatic (two notable exceptions being woodlice and hexapods, which are both purely terrestrial) and are characterized by having biramous appendages.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The most abundant group of pancrustaceans are the terrestrial hexapods, which comprise insects, diplurans, springtails, and proturans, with six thoracic legs.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The phylogeny of the major extant arthropod groups has been an area of considerable interest and dispute.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] Recent studies strongly suggest that Crustacea, as traditionally defined, is paraphyletic, with Hexapoda having evolved from within it, so that Crustacea and Hexapoda form a clade, Pancrustacea.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] The position of Myriapoda, Chelicerata and Pancrustacea remains unclear as of April 2012.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p01] In some studies, Myriapoda is grouped with Chelicerata (forming Myriochelata); in other studies, Myriapoda is grouped with Pancrustacea (forming Mandibulata), or Myriapoda may be sister to Chelicerata plus Pancrustacea.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Crustaceans such as crabs, lobsters, crayfish, shrimp, and prawns have long been part of human cuisine, and are now raised commercially.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Insects and their grubs are at least as nutritious as meat, and are eaten both raw and cooked in many cultures, though not most European, Hindu, and Islamic cultures.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Cooked tarantulas are considered a delicacy in Cambodia, and by the Piaroa Indians of southern Venezuela, after the highly irritant hairs – the spider's main defence system – are removed.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Humans also unintentionally eat arthropods in other foods, and food safety regulations lay down acceptable contamination levels for different kinds of food material.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] The intentional cultivation of arthropods and other small animals for human food, referred to as minilivestock, is now emerging in animal husbandry as an ecologically sound concept.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Commercial butterfly breeding provides Lepidoptera stock to butterfly conservatories, educational exhibits, schools, research facilities, and cultural events.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Besides pollinating, bees produce honey, which is the basis of a rapidly growing industry and international trade.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] The red dye cochineal, produced from a Central American species of insect, was economically important to the Aztecs and Mayans.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] While the region was under Spanish control, it became Mexico's second most-lucrative export, and is now regaining some of the ground it lost to synthetic competitors.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Shellac, a resin secreted by a species of insect native to southern Asia, was historically used in great quantities for many applications in which it has mostly been replaced by synthetic resins, but it is still used in woodworking and as a food additive.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] The blood of horseshoe crabs contains a clotting agent, limulus amebocyte lysate, which is now used to test that antibiotics and kidney machines are free of dangerous bacteria, and to detect spinal meningitis.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Forensic entomology uses evidence provided by arthropods to establish the time and sometimes the place of death of a human, and in some cases the cause.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Recently insects have also gained attention as potential sources of drugs and other medicinal substances.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] The relative simplicity of the arthropods' body plan, allowing them to move on a variety of surfaces both on land and in water, have made them useful as models for robotics.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] The redundancy provided by segments allows arthropods and biomimetic robots to move normally, even with damaged or lost appendages.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Although arthropods are the most numerous phylum on Earth, and thousands of arthropod species are venomous, they inflict relatively few serious bites and stings on humans.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Far more serious are the effects on humans of diseases like malaria carried by blood-sucking insects.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Other blood-sucking insects infect livestock with diseases that kill many animals and greatly reduce the usefulness of others.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Ticks can cause tick paralysis and several parasite-borne diseases in humans.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] A few of the closely related mites also infest humans, causing intense itching, and others cause allergic diseases, including hay fever, asthma, and eczema.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Many species of arthropods, principally insects but also mites, are agricultural and forest pests.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] The mite *Varroa destructor* has become the largest single problem faced by beekeepers worldwide.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Efforts to control arthropod pests by large-scale use of pesticides have caused long-term effects on human health and on biodiversity.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Increasing arthropod resistance to pesticides has led to the development of integrated pest management using a wide range of measures including biological control.
[src:arthropod/arthropod-p02] Predatory mites may be useful in controlling some mite pests.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM was founded in 1899 under the name the "Society of American Bacteriologists." In December 1960, it was renamed the "American Society for Microbiology.".
[src:arthropod/asm-press] In June of 2026, it was again renamed "ASM" to reflect its global reach.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM is a global community shaping the future of the microbial sciences to tackle some of the world's most pressing challenges.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Established in 1899, ASM is the home for microbial scientists from around the globe to connect, learn, discover and prepare for the future.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] We connect with millions of experts and harness their science to serve humanity.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] From climate change, antimicrobial resistance, industrial, basic and applied microbiology, ASM is a leader in scientific publishing, stands for open science and advocates for evidence-based public policies.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM brings together scientists, educators, clinicians, students, and professionals from around the globe to advance discovery, share knowledge, and address the world's most pressing challenges through microbial science.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] An ASM Membership gives you access to a wide range of benefits designed to support your science, your career and your community: Save big with exclusive discounts on ASM’s premier conferences, webinars and professional development courses.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Connect globally with microbiologists and stay on the cutting edge of your field.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Publish for less with discounted rates in ASM’s top-ranked peer-reviewed journals.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Know your worth with access to ASM’s exclusive Microbiology Careers Salary Survey.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Advance your career through grants, awards, and mentorship programs tailored to help you thrive.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM hosts meetings and conferences, including the annual meeting ASM Microbe, that provide forums to explore microbiology topics.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM Microbe, a combination of what was formerly the ASM General Meeting and the Interscience Conference on Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy (ICAAC), is now 3 meetings in 1.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM accepts format-neutral submissions for all primary research journals since 2018.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The society also publishes *Microcosm*, a quarterly news magazine for members.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Through its publishing arm ASM Press, the society publishes books covering diverse topics.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Wiley is co-publisher and distributor of the ASM Press books and ebooks.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The American Academy of Microbiology (AAM) is the honorific leadership group within the American Society of Microbiology, a professional organization for microbiologists.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The academy is currently composed of over 2,600 Fellows.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Academy leadership is divided into four groups: the Academy Governors, the Academy Leadership Nominating Subcommittee, the Subcommittee on Awards, and the Subcommittee on Elections.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The original organization was dissolved in 1970, when new bylaws were accepted.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] As of 2020, each year 65 new members are elected.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] That number has fluctuated historically to as many as 110.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Membership is not exclusive to American residents, and indeed 19% of members currently live outside the U.S.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The 2021 class of Fellows included representatives of 11 countries, including France.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] In 2021, there were 150 nominations, and 130 nominations the following year.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The call for nominations begins in August.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Only current AAM fellows can nominate a new fellow, and that nomination must be supported by at least two other AAM fellows.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Candidates cannot apply for fellowship directly, but can reach out to current fellows to seek nomination.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The Sub-committee of Elections and the Academy Governors, which are composed of AAM members elected by the entire AAM membership, then vote to approve of the nominations.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Members of the AAM are elected through an annual peer-reviewed process based on their records of scientific achievements that have advanced microbiology.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The academy administers ASM scientific achievement awards that honor important contributions to basic and applied research, microbiology education, and scientific and professional leadership.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] There is no limit to the number of times a person can be nominated, nor an age limit for nomination.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Notable academy members include Anthony Fauci (former director of the National Institute for Allergies and Infectious Disease) and Rita Colwell (former director of the National Science Foundation).
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The AAM holds colloquia, sometimes in conjunction with other scientific societies, on topics pertinent to public interests and the expertises of its members.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Topics include climate change, One Health, and clinical diagnostics.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Reports from the colloquia are made publicly available.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] In addition to communicating via colloquium reports, mBio, a journal launched by ASM in 2009, offers an ‘AAM track’ where AAM members are allowed to submit one manuscript per year.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Fellows are required to submit two reviews per submission, make modifications that address the reviewers’ comments, then submit the revised version to the mBio editors.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] However, submission does not guarantee acceptance.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The AAM also selects an Honorary Diversity Lecturer.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] This award, aimed to attract more under-represented minorities to the field, is given to a mid-to-senior level scientist who is both highly accomplished and an "outstanding" speaker.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The American College of Microbiology (ACM) certified microbiologists and immunologists and provided accreditation of postdoctoral training programs.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM produces eight podcasts, including *This Week in Microbiology*, *This Week in Virology*, and *This Week in Parasitism*, hosted by Vincent Racaniello.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] *Mundo de los Microbios* hosted by Gary Toranzos, is ASM's weekly Spanish-language podcast.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] *Meet the Microbiologist* is a podcast hosted by Julie Wolf, Ph.D., that showcases the people behind the scientific discoveries in various cutting-edge areas of the microbial sciences.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM empowers members to advocate for the highest standards in scientific practice and provides members opportunities to advocate for evidence-based scientific policy.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] In 2011, ASM made a concerted effort to address the lack of visibility of its policy arm, specifically in promoting the interests of clinical microbiologists.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] The Public and Scientific Affairs Board Professional Affairs Committee and Committee on Laboratory Practices was active in influencing policy decisions through Congress, the Clinical Laboratory Coalition, the FDA, and the CDC.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM restructured its advocacy program to enhance its effectiveness in Washington, D.C., and its expansion to the Branches and various local communities.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] In 2018, ASM engaged members of Congress and issued statements in conjunction with Congressional hearings focusing on recent outbreaks of vaccine-preventable diseases like the measles.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM members sent nearly 2,000 messages to Members of Congress in support of increased science funding.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] Noteworthy is the appreciation of ASM by CDC, since raising the caps made specifically possible the construction of the new biocontainment lab.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] In 2018, ASM advocated successfully for establishing PACCARB (President's Advisory Council for Combatting Antibiotic Resistance Bacteria) into the law (from an Obama administration Executive Order), by including language in the Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness and Advancing Innovation Act.
[src:arthropod/asm-press] ASM convened a meeting with more than 20 stakeholder groups to discuss a collective path forward for federally-focused advocacy in support of microbiome research.
